Jeevansathi.com Exploratory Text analysis

20/10/2020

Using the Profile Description variable, here is a basic exploratory analysis of user profiles on Jeevansathi.com. We have a total of about 577,000 profiles in our dataset (September Scrape).

Frequency Table (Normalised)

The following frequency table is normalised by the number of profiles for each category (Male, Female and Overall).
Common English Stopwords (is, an, the etc. ) have been removed and some other stopwords have been added to the negative list.
Here is a list of them : (can be ignored while reading)

We also lemmatize the text by bringing words to their roots. For example, loving, lover and love turn into love.

Once that is done, we generate 1-grams, 2-grams and 3-grams (collection of 1,2 and 3 word phrases) and calculate their percentage frequency.

We now look at the difference in the frequency more formally by using a Keyness score which implements a chi-squared statistic that is signed positively if the observed value in the target exceeds its expected value. Here the target is female profiles and reference is male profiles. A higher score shows an indication of how much the word is more likely to be seen in the target group.

Co-occurance of words in male and female profiles

We first create a matrix that gives the co-occurance of words occuring at least 1000 times in the data. We then plot the matrix into a network diagram, edges of which show the co-occurrences of the words.

Female Network of Co-occurances

Male Network of Co-occurances

These tables and diagrams were generated out of only 1 variable (about the user) of the many (About 75) in the complete matrimonial dataset and hence there is a lot more to be seen.
